      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This lesson begins by orienting learners to the term 'Texican,' a historically significant identity during the Mexican Texas period. We will clarify its meaning and set the stage for deeper exploration of Texican culture and history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Explore the term 'Texican' and its historical context</li><li>Understand the cultural origins during Mexican Texas era (1820-1836)</li><li>Engage in interactive activities to assess prior knowledge</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>We will start with a poll to gauge what you already know about 'Texicans' and then create a word cloud to visualize common associations.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on any prior knowledge or assumptions you have about the term 'Texican' before we begin.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid confusing 'Texican' with similar terms like 'Texian' or 'Texan' without understanding their distinct historical contexts.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
