      "h": "The Role of Indigenous Peoples in Texican Life",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans engaged with Native American tribes in multifaceted ways, shaping cultural exchange and political relationships that influenced the region's history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans had complex interactions including trade, conflict, and alliances</li><li>Shared cultural practices influenced by indigenous neighbors</li><li>Indigenous groups impacted Texican identity and regional dynamics</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican traders might exchange goods with Caddo tribes, adopting some indigenous customs in the process.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how these interactions could affect Texican cultural identity and security.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid viewing Texican-indigenous relations as solely hostile; they were often cooperative and culturally influential.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
