    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Geographic Distribution of Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Settlements concentrated near rivers: Brazos, Colorado, and Guadalupe</li><li>Proximity to water essential for farming and transport</li><li>Settlements often formed small, self-sufficient communities</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlements were strategically located near rivers to support agriculture and trade, fostering communities that balanced independence with Mexican governance. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Austin’s Old Three Hundred settled primarily along the Brazos River, leveraging fertile land and water access.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify reasons why rivers were critical to Texican settlement success.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the importance of natural resources in settlement location decisions.</p></div></div>",
