    "id": "slide15",
    "eyebrow": "Lifestyle",
    "num": "15",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Lifestyle</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Daily Life and Economy</h2><ul><li>Agriculture was the economic backbone: corn, cattle, and cotton</li><li>Ranching and cattle drives became prominent</li><li>Communities combined Mexican and Anglo traditions in daily life</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican lifestyle centered on farming and ranching, blending Mexican land use practices with Anglo-American agricultural methods, creating a unique frontier economy. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican ranchers adopted Mexican vaquero techniques alongside Anglo cattle herding practices.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican economic activities reflected cultural blending.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican economy was purely Anglo or Mexican without hybrid influences.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 15",
      "h": "Deep Dive: Economic and Cultural Synthesis in Texican Life",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican lifestyle centered on farming and ranching, blending Mexican land use practices with Anglo-American agricultural methods, creating a unique frontier economy.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Agriculture was the economic backbone: corn, cattle, and cotton</li><li>Ranching and cattle drives became prominent</li><li>Communities combined Mexican and Anglo traditions in daily life</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican ranchers adopted Mexican vaquero techniques alongside Anglo cattle herding practices.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Describe how Texican economic activities reflected cultural blending.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican economy was purely Anglo or Mexican without hybrid influences.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
    }
