    "id": "slide26",
    "eyebrow": "Texican Social Structure",
    "num": "26",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">26</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texican Social Structure</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Social Roles and Community Life of Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texican society blended Mexican, Spanish, and indigenous customs</li><li>Communities were often rural with strong family and religious ties</li><li>Social roles included ranchers, farmers, merchants, and militia members</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican social life was a fusion of cultural influences, with families forming the core of rural communities. Their roles extended beyond agriculture to include commerce and defense, reflecting a multifaceted society. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican rancher might also serve in the local militia, illustrating the overlap of economic and military roles in community life.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican social roles supported both daily life and community defense.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the diversity of Texican occupations and assuming a solely agrarian lifestyle.</p></div></div>",
