    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">28</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources in Texican History</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Using Primary Documents to Trace Texican Roles</h2><ul><li>Primary sources include letters, government records, and militia rosters</li><li>They provide firsthand perspectives on Texican political and military actions</li><li>Analyzing these sources reveals complexities and contested interpretations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary documents are essential for understanding Texican history, offering direct evidence of their roles and viewpoints. Careful analysis helps uncover nuances often missed in secondary accounts. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A militia roster from 1835 lists Texican volunteers, showing community involvement in the revolution.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a primary source excerpt to identify Texican motivations and actions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying solely on secondary summaries without engaging with original documents.</p></div></div>",
