    "num": "37",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">37</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources Overview</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">What Are Primary Sources?</h2><ul><li>Original documents or artifacts created during the period studied</li><li>Include letters, government records, diaries, maps, and newspapers</li><li>Provide firsthand accounts and direct evidence of historical events</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources are the raw materials of history, offering direct insight into the lives and events of the past. For Texican history, these sources reveal perspectives often missing from secondary narratives. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican settler describing daily life in Mexican Texas offers unfiltered details about culture and challenges.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify which types of documents you might find useful to understand Texican experiences.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Confusing primary sources with secondary interpretations or summaries.</p></div></div>",
