    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">38</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Collections</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Archives for Texican History</h2><ul><li>Texas State Library and Archives: Republic of Texas documents</li><li>University of North Texas: Primary source lesson sets</li><li>Southern Historical Collection: Letters and diaries from settlers</li><li>Yale and Berkeley Libraries: Digital collections of Mexican Texas records</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Several institutions maintain extensive collections of primary sources relevant to Texican history, offering access to government records, personal correspondence, and legal documents from the Mexican Texas period. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The Texas State Library holds official Republic of Texas records, including land grants and legislative acts that shaped Texican settlement.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explore one archive’s online catalog and identify a document related to Texican settlement or governance.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all archives have the same types of documents or that digital access is always comprehensive.</p></div></div>",
