    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">41</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Bias and Perspective</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Recognizing Bias in Texican Documents</h2><ul><li>Authors may emphasize certain events or omit others</li><li>Political documents often reflect government agendas</li><li>Personal writings reveal subjective experiences</li><li>Language and tone can signal attitudes or prejudices</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Bias is inherent in all historical documents. Recognizing it helps learners critically assess the reliability and perspective of Texican primary sources. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A government proclamation may downplay conflicts with Native tribes to promote settlement.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify potential biases in a Texican government record versus a settler’s diary entry.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming official documents are objective or that personal accounts are fully accurate.</p></div></div>",
