    "num": "42",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">42</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Language and Translation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Challenges of Language in Texican Sources</h2><ul><li>Many documents are in Spanish or use archaic terms</li><li>Translation can affect meaning and nuance</li><li>Understanding historical context aids interpretation</li><li>Consulting bilingual resources improves accuracy</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Language barriers and translation issues complicate analysis of Texican primary sources, requiring careful attention to preserve original meanings. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Spanish land grant uses legal terms that may not have direct English equivalents, affecting interpretation.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how translation choices might influence your understanding of a document’s content.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying on literal translations without context or expert guidance.</p></div></div>",
