    "eyebrow": "Document Types",
    "num": "43",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">43</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Document Types</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Common Primary Source Types in Texican History</h2><ul><li>Government records: land grants, laws, census data</li><li>Personal letters and diaries: daily life and opinions</li><li>Newspapers and broadsides: public announcements and propaganda</li><li>Maps and surveys: geographic and settlement information</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Different document types offer varied insights into Texican history, from official policies to personal experiences and public discourse. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A land grant document shows legal ownership, while a diary entry reveals settler emotions about land disputes.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Match document types to the kinds of historical questions they best answer.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Using one document type exclusively, limiting perspective.</p></div></div>",
