      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This checkpoint reinforces document analysis skills by applying them to a new Texican source, preparing learners for independent research.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.fau.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Select a primary source excerpt provided</li><li>Identify author, date, and purpose</li><li>Analyze potential biases and language challenges</li><li>Summarize what the source reveals about Texican history</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A newspaper announcement from 1835 reflects political tensions before the Texas Revolution.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief analysis addressing the bullet points for your chosen source.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking context or failing to identify bias.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.fau.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
