    "id": "slide49",
    "eyebrow": "Indigenous Influence",
    "num": "49",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">49</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Indigenous Influence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Origin of the Name 'Texas'</h2><ul><li>The name 'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'táysha,' meaning 'friends' or 'allies.'</li><li>Caddo people were prominent indigenous inhabitants of the region.</li><li>This indigenous origin reflects early cultural interactions shaping the region's identity.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The word 'Texas' originates from the Caddo language, specifically the term 'táysha,' which means 'friends' or 'allies.' This highlights the significant indigenous influence on the region's identity before and during the Texican period. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The use of 'Texas' as a place name demonstrates how indigenous languages contributed to place-naming, reflecting relationships and alliances important to early inhabitants.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Reflect on how indigenous words like 'táysha' influence modern place names and what this reveals about cultural interactions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming 'Texas' is solely a Spanish or Anglo invention without indigenous roots.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 49",
      "h": "Deep Dive: Linguistic Roots and Cultural Significance of 'Texas'",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The word 'Texas' originates from the Caddo language, specifically the term 'táysha,' which means 'friends' or 'allies.' This highlights the significant indigenous influence on the region's identity before and during the Texican period.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>The name 'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'táysha,' meaning 'friends' or 'allies.'</li><li>Caddo people were prominent indigenous inhabitants of the region.</li><li>This indigenous origin reflects early cultural interactions shaping the region's identity.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The use of 'Texas' as a place name demonstrates how indigenous languages contributed to place-naming, reflecting relationships and alliances important to early inhabitants.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on how indigenous words like 'táysha' influence modern place names and what this reveals about cultural interactions.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming 'Texas' is solely a Spanish or Anglo invention without indigenous roots.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
    },
    "words": "wordcloud1-texican-associations"
