    "id": "slide50",
    "eyebrow": "Indigenous Influence",
    "num": "50",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">50</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Indigenous Influence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Caddo and Other Indigenous Peoples in Mexican Texas</h2><ul><li>Caddo were among the most influential indigenous groups in East Texas.</li><li>Their social and political structures impacted early Texican settlements.</li><li>Interactions included trade, alliances, and cultural exchange.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Caddo and other indigenous groups played a vital role in shaping the social and cultural landscape of Mexican Texas. Their established communities influenced settlement patterns and relationships with Texicans. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican settlers often engaged in trade with Caddo communities, exchanging goods and knowledge that affected daily life and survival.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify ways indigenous social structures might have influenced Texican governance or community organization.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking indigenous agency by portraying Native Americans only as obstacles or victims.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 50",
      "h": "Deep Dive: Indigenous Political and Social Influence on Texicans",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The Caddo and other indigenous groups played a vital role in shaping the social and cultural landscape of Mexican Texas. Their established communities influenced settlement patterns and relationships with Texicans.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Caddo were among the most influential indigenous groups in East Texas.</li><li>Their social and political structures impacted early Texican settlements.</li><li>Interactions included trade, alliances, and cultural exchange.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican settlers often engaged in trade with Caddo communities, exchanging goods and knowledge that affected daily life and survival.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify ways indigenous social structures might have influenced Texican governance or community organization.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking indigenous agency by portraying Native Americans only as obstacles or victims.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
    }
